The presumption of law was against joint liability, but it could be rebutted by the order of the stipulatione: for if the answer were made to the same question put by two stipulators successively, there could not be two obligations, because the first would be invalidated by the interposition of the second, Dig. 45. 2. 12. pn, so that correality or joint liability results from the principle ‘ubi ambigua oratio est, commo· dissimum est id accipi, quo res, de qua agitur, magis valeat quam pereat' Dig. 34. 5. 12.
